“And the turtles, of course...all the turtles are free, as turtles and, maybe, all creatures should be.”- “Yertle the Turtle,” by Dr. SeussDid you know that the ancestors of today’s Sea Turtles coexisted with, and in some cases pre-dated, dinosaurs first appearing in the world’s oceans over 150 million years ago?  These majestic creatures have a complex life cycle that depends on protected reefs, open ocean, and nesting beaches on land all around the world. Because of their unique traits, Sea Turtles are vulnerable to all kinds of things like ocean plastic, beach front development and artificial lighting which confuses nesting mothers and hatchlings, leaving them stranded.  Like many species today, multiple challenging threats are impacting the world’s Sea Turtles making it critical that we get creative and use every tool in the toolkit to secure a future for these beautiful and gentle ancient mariners.The Wildlife Friendly Enterprise Network is thrilled to announce that we are working on the launch of Sea Turtle Friendly™ tourism—the world’s first global Sea Turtle standards! By partnering with the travel and hospitality industry, as well as local communities, Sea Turtle Friendly™ will give tourists opportunities to contribute directly to Sea Turtle conservation by choosing certified destinations for their journeys.The Problem: Sea Turtles are Globally at Risk From Human-Induced ThreatsSea Turtles are a much-loved symbol of the tropics and an indicator species for the health of the marine environment.  Adventurous tourists seek out snorkeling or diving opportunities to see them swimming in the wild. We've seen Sea Turtles featured in many movies such as "Finding Nemo," and they are an iconic species in most tropical, coastal regions.  As peaceful and graceful creatures, the world would be a poorer place without Sea Turtles.  But sadly, all 7 species of Sea Turtles are included on the IUCN “Red List” of Threatened Species, and two (Hawksbill, Kemp’s Ridley) are in the category of Critically Endangered. This means that we are at risk of losing these animals forever due to many threats including impacts from fishing, hunting, coastal development, pollution, disease, and climate change.When tourists visit a place where Sea Turtles visit or nest, they may be adding further stresses to these fragile species--the lights from hotel rooms, plastic pollution, and even stress from snorkelers that come too close can harm these animals and their future. You probably have heard that cutting open plastic rings from soda cans can help save Sea Turtles, but there is much more you can do. The Solution: Engaging Tourists & the Hospitality Sector as Partners in Conservation Tourists have an opportunity to support Sea Turtle conservation by changing their behaviors and simply selecting resorts and tour operators that care about the future of these species. Sea Turtle Friendly™ will work together with its partners to reduce direct impacts caused by development and recreational activities.Travelers can also make smart choices in choosing not to purchase carvings or other items made from Sea Turtle shell, and they can instead choose to support smaller businesses that support conservation. Sea Turtle Friendly™ will provide new and sustainable livelihood opportunities for coastal communities that might otherwise turn to an illegal trade in meat, eggs, or turtle parts (e.g. shell).  Tourists can also report egg poaching or the sale of eggs or meat if they observe these harmful activities.  And importantly, tourists can educate their families, friends, and others about the many threats facing these amazing reptiles, including irresponsible tourism. We are developing educational materials for Sea Turtle Friendly™ resorts and tours, which will teach tourists about Sea Turtles and all of the critical actions that they can take to ensure that these species survive for future generations to enjoy.You Can Help Create a Balance Between Sea Turtles and Tourism!We are incredibly honored to be collaborating closely with WIDECAST (Wider Caribbean Sea Turtle Conservation Network), which has provided the framework for our conservation best practices. We are also fortunate to have received one of only 7 State of the World's Sea Turtles (SWOT) grants awarded in 2016! This grant awarded $1,000 for our project, and we are seeking additional funding to support this important work. Sea Turtle Friendly™ will launch in the Philippines in early 2017, and we plan to expand the project next to Florida, Latin America and the Caribbean if we meet our funding goals. By donating to this project, you are directly supporting:
Certification of the very first Sea Turtle Friendly™ hotels and tour operators through our expert driven standards; 
The creation of educational materials for tourists; 
Trainings for field staff; 
Expansion of the program to the other hotspots where Sea Turtles live
We are a very small non-profit organization. We rely on grant funding and philanthropic donations to support our work. This allows us to have a maximum impact on the species we work to save. 100% of your donation will directly support our conservation work--our standards, trainings, educational materials, and audits of the sites that we hope to certify. Our work is unique among conservation organizations because we aim to change private industry practices, which often have the largest effects on wildlife and the environment.We invite you to envision a world where wildlife and communities not only coexist but thrive, where tourists are engaged as partners in conservation, and where consumers, companies and communities are empowered to be catalysts for change.Even if you can't donate, please help us by spreading the word about our efforts to save Sea Turtles through tourism! Thank you!
